Old school C hacker here.  Can someone explain to me like I&#x27;m five how this is different from<p>assert(p != NULL);  // unrecoverable error<p>if (p == NULL) {<p><pre><code>    // no buffer for you but we&#x27;ll continue

    perror(&quot;malloc&quot;);

    return (0);

}</code></pre>

To elaborate on this, a C implementation of objc_msgSend would look something like this:<p><pre><code>    id objc_msgSend(id self, SEL _cmd, args...) {
        IMP methodImplementation = ...; // look up the method however
        return methodImplementation(self, _cmd, args...);
    }
</code></pre>
But there is no facility in C that lets you take arbitrary additional arguments and then pass them all to another function unchanged.<p>(In theory you could accomplish this using variadic functions. But then every method would have to take a va_list for its parameters instead of just taking a regular parameter list, breaking the idea that ObjC methods are just C functions with two implicit parameters. It would also be substantially slower.)
